The increase in counterfeit goods on the black market has the potential to destroy the local economy and could lead to more unemployment, according to experts. This follows an announcement by the Gauteng provincial government that counterfeit goods worth R5 billion were seized in Gauteng alone last year. Paul Ramara, a partner at Spoor & Fisher, who specialise in trademark litigation and anti-counterfeiting, said counterfeiting affects our economy as it leads to loss of customs duties, value added tax and the normal tax that would have been paid on the goods. â€œThis has an impact on the economy in the...